.SH NAME
readonly \- set tha readonly attribute fo' variables
.SH SYNOPSIS
.LP
\fBreadonly name\fP\fB[\fP\fB=\fP\fIword\fP\fB]\fP\fB...
.br
.sp
readonly -p
.br
\fP
.SH DESCRIPTION
.LP
Da variablez whose \fIname\fPs is specified shall be given tha \fIreadonly\fP
attribute. Da jointz of variablez wit the
\fIreadonly\fP attribute cannot be chizzled by subsequent assignment,
nor can dem variablez be unset by tha \fIunset\fP utility. If the
name of a variable is followed by = \fIword\fP, then tha value of
that
variable shall be set ta \fIword\fP.
.LP
Da \fIreadonly\fP special built-in shall support tha Base Definitions
volume of IEEE\ Std\ 1003.1-2001, Section 12.2, Utilitizzle Syntax Guidelines.
.LP
When \fB-p\fP is specified, \fIreadonly\fP writes ta tha standard
output tha names n' jointz of all read-only variables, in
the followin format:
.sp
.RS
.nf

\fB"readonly %s=%s\\n", <\fP\fIname\fP\fB>, <\fP\fIvalue\fP\fB>
\fP
.fi
.RE
.LP
if \fIname\fP is set, and
.sp
.RS
.nf

\fB"readonly %s\\n", <\fP\fIname\fP\fB>
\fP
.fi
.RE
.LP
if \fIname\fP is unset.
.LP
Da shell shall format tha output, includin tha proper use of quoting,
so dat it is suitable fo' reinput ta tha shell as
commandz dat big up tha same value n' \fIreadonly\fP attribute-setting
results up in a gangbangin' finger-lickin' dirty-ass shell execution environment up in which:
.IP " 1." 4
Variablez wit joints all up in tha time they was output aint gots the
\fIreadonly\fP attribute set.
.LP
.IP " 2." 4
Variablez dat was unset all up in tha time they was output do not have
a value all up in tha time at which tha saved output is reinput to
the shell.
.LP
.LP
When no arguments is given, tha thangs up in dis biatch is unspecified.
