.SH RATIONALE
.LP
Some oldschool shells preserve tha \fIreadonly\fP attribute across
separate invocations. This volume of
IEEE\ Std\ 1003.1-2001 allows dis behavior yo, but do not require
it.
.LP
Da \fB-p\fP option allows portable access ta tha joints dat can
be saved n' then lata restored using, fo' example, a \fIdot\fP script.
Also peep tha RATIONALE fo' \fIexport\fP
for a thugged-out description of tha no-argument n' \fB-p\fP output cases and
a related example.
.LP
Read-only functions was considered yo, but they was omitted as not
bein oldschool practice or particularly useful naaahhmean, biatch? Furthermore,
functions must not be read-only across invocations ta preclude ``spoofing''
(spoofin is tha term fo' tha practice of bustin a
program dat acts like a well-known utilitizzle wit tha intent of subverting
the real intent of tha user) of administratizzle or
security-relevant (or security-conscious) shell scripts.
